            <bioghist id="aspace_ed07403c8774641177009e66cb8865c5">
               <head>Biographical / Historical</head>
               <p>Rev. George Fountain was a pastor who most likely traveled to France with the Young Men's Christian Association to minister and provide medical aid to soldiers during World War I. During his service, he photographed various battle sites and towns, monuments, soldiers, and military aircraft, vehicles, and arms.</p>
            </bioghist>
            <scopecontent id="aspace_60ae3a1f72f9268a73b1d3e7743e1883">
               <head>Scope and Contents</head>
               <p>This series contains George Fountain's glass plate negatives and photographic negatives depicting scenes from World War I, including battle sites in France; American, French, and German soldiers and aviators; aircraft, vehicles, and armaments; buildings, bridges, and monuments; and the aftermath of bombing raids on cities and towns. Among the images are Sargeant Alvin York standing on the hill where he faced a German machine gun battalion and General John J. Pershing at a French aviation camp. Also included are original negative sleeves with Fountain's handwritten captions, a wooden crate belonging to Fountain, and a 20th century newsclipping about glass negatives.</p>
            </scopecontent>
